# Email Voice and Tone — FT.com Register

All prose in `daily_options_email.py` (market summary, section headers, alert text)
follows the Financial Times editorial style. This is a hard standard — do not revert
to informal trader slang when editing.

## The Core Principle

> Write as if a financially literate analyst produced the copy after reviewing a
> Bloomberg terminal. Measured, precise, authoritative. Let the numbers do the work.

---

## Word Choices — Approved vs Banned

### Index movements

| ✅ Use | ❌ Never use |
|---|---|
| declined, fell, edged lower, was little changed | sold off, got hit, cratered, tanked, dumped |
| advanced, rose, edged higher | ripped, popped, squeezed, ran |
| fell sharply / rose sharply (for > 1.5%) | nuked, exploded, went parabolic |
| outperformed, underperformed | leading, lagging (too informal) |

### Volatility

| ✅ Use | ❌ Never use |
|---|---|
| the Vix (capitalised, "the" as article) | VIX (all-caps), "vol" |
| rose, eased, edged higher/lower | spiked, crushed, got smashed |

### Indices and instruments

| ✅ Use | ❌ Never use |
|---|---|
| the S&P 500 | SPY, "the S&P" |
| technology stocks, the Nasdaq Composite | QQQ, "Nasdaq" alone |
| small-cap stocks | "small-caps" |
| the 200-day moving average | "the 200-day", "200ma" |
| the eight-day exponential average | "8 EMA", "the 8" |

### Regime and strategy language

| ✅ Use | ❌ Never use |
|---|---|
| the regime is indeterminate / constructive / unfavourable | "the tape is choppy" |
| premium collection remains the primary return driver | "let theta work" |
| no new directional exposure is warranted | "wait for the market to show its hand" |
| time decay accrued | "theta burned" |
| the strategy is weighted towards | "the job is to…" |
| stop placement warrants a review | "check your stops are tight" |

---

## Punctuation

- **Em dash (—)** for genuine parenthetical asides: *"The S&P 500 declined 1.4% — a 9th consecutive close below the 200-day."*
- No exclamation marks, ever.
- Percentages: always `%` (not "per cent" — this is digital, not FT print).
- Numbers: `$557`, `22.8`, `3.7%` — always specific, never rounded to vague ranges.
- Sentences end with a full stop. No trailing ellipses in body copy.

## Sentence Structure

- **Short declarative sentences first**, interpretation second.
  - ✅ *"The S&P 500 declined 1.2%. Technology stocks underperformed the broader index."*
  - ❌ *"SPY sold off hard and the Nasdaq got hit even harder with tech leading the way down."*
- Maximum two clauses joined by a comma. If you need three, use two sentences.
- Never start a sentence with "And" or "But" in body copy.

## Forward-Looking Language

Morning edition:
> *"Investors will be focused on X, as well as Y."*

Evening edition:
> *"Key factors to monitor overnight include X, as well as Y."*

Never use bullet lists for watch items in the narrative paragraph — keep it prose.

## Section Headers and Labels

- Sentence case for headers: *"Long positions"*, not *"LONG POSITIONS"* (CSS handles caps)
- "In the news" for the Marketaux block — not "Negative headlines", "Top stories", or "Market news"
- Alert box: plain statement — *"CHRD covered call approaching in-the-money"* — not *"⚠️ CHRD is getting close to being called away!!!"*

---

## Checking Your Copy

Before committing any change to `_build_market_summary()` or related functions,
read the draft aloud. If it sounds like a Reddit post or a Discord message, revise it.
If it sounds like an FT Markets briefing, ship it.
